headless service communicate to other pod using dns name is it true?

yes, Pods communicate directly using this DNS — not through a virtual IP. Even if the pod restarts and gets a new IP, the DNS name stays the same. This is why StatefulSet needs headless service — so slaves can always find the master by name, not by IP."

Normal Service vs Headless Service

+----------------------+---------------------------+-----------------------------+
| Feature              | Normal Service            | Headless Service            |
+----------------------+---------------------------+-----------------------------+
| clusterIP            | Has IP (e.g. 10.96.0.1)   | None                        |
| DNS resolves to      | Single virtual IP         | Direct pod IPs              |
| Load balancing       | Yes (random)              | No (client chooses pod)     |
| Use case             | Stateless apps            | StatefulSets / Databases    |
+----------------------+---------------------------+-----------------------------+

Types of Services Summary

Service Type   | ClusterIP      | Access               | Use Case
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ClusterIP      | Auto assigned  | Internal only        | Default internal service
NodePort       | Auto assigned  | External via Node IP | Dev/testing
LoadBalancer   | Auto assigned  | External via ELB     | Production
Headless       | None           | Direct pod IP        | Stateful apps, DBs

How Headless DNS works:

Normal Service DNS:
mysql.default.svc.cluster.local
        ↓
    10.96.0.1  (single VIP — you don't know which pod)


Headless Service DNS:
mysql.default.svc.cluster.local
        ↓
    10.244.1.10  (pod-0 IP)
    10.244.1.11  (pod-1 IP)
    10.244.1.12  (pod-2 IP)

Each pod ALSO gets its own DNS:	
mysql-0.mysql.default.svc.cluster.local → 10.244.1.10
mysql-1.mysql.default.svc.cluster.local → 10.244.1.11
mysql-2.mysql.default.svc.cluster.local → 10.244.1.12


Even if mysql-0 pod restarts and gets a new IP
The DNS name mysql-0.mysql.default.svc.cluster.local still works
It always resolves to wherever mysql-0 is running


This is why StatefulSet needs Headless Service:

Without headless:
  slave → VIP → random pod (could hit another slave!) ❌

With headless:
  slave → mysql-0.mysql... → directly to master ✅


Normal Service uses kube-proxy + iptables rules:

Client Pod
    │
    │ calls mysql.default.svc.cluster.local
    ▼
DNS resolves to VIP → 10.96.0.1
    │
    ▼
kube-proxy (runs on every node)
    │
    ▼
iptables / IPVS rules
    │
    ├──→ Pod-0 (10.244.1.10)
    ├──→ Pod-1 (10.244.1.11)
    └──→ Pod-2 (10.244.1.12)

Who does the actual routing?
kube-proxy — runs as a DaemonSet on every node. It watches the Kubernetes API and writes iptables rules on each node.

iptables rules (auto-created by kube-proxy):

VIP 10.96.0.1 never actually exists on any machine
It's a virtual IP — only lives in iptables rules
kube-proxy intercepts and rewrites the packet destination

How kube-proxy knows which pods are healthy:

kube-proxy watches → Endpoints object
                          │
        ┌─────────────────┼──────────────────┐
        ▼                 ▼                  ▼
   10.244.1.10       10.244.1.11        10.244.1.12
   (Ready ✅)        (Ready ✅)         (NotReady ❌)

kube-proxy removes NotReady pods from iptables rules
→ traffic never hits unhealthy pods
